softness.title: Softness
softness.description: Softness of the constraint. Recommend 0.8 to 1. Describes the percentage of limits where movement is free. Beyond this softness percentage, the limit is gradually enforced until the "hard" (1.0) limit is reached.

biasFactor.title: Bias Factor
biasFactor.description: Bias factor of the constraint. Recommend 0.3 +/- approximately 0.3. Strength with which constraint resists zeroth order (angular, not angular velocity) limit violation.

relaxationFactor.title: Relaxation Factor
relaxationFactor.description: Relaxation factor of the constraint. Recommend to keep this near 1. The lower the value, the less the constraint will fight velocities which violate the angular limits.

swingSpan1.title: Swing 1 Limit
swingSpan1.description: The Swing 1 Limit limits the rotation around the swing axis. Swing 1 Limit limits an axis of rotation orthogonal to the twist axis and Swing Limit 2. The limit angle is symmetric. Therefore, a value of 20 will limit the rotation between -20 and 20 degrees.

swingSpan2.title: Swing 2 Limit
swingSpan2.description: The Swing 2 Limit limits the rotation around the swing axis. Swing 2 Limit limits an axis of rotation orthogonal to the twist axis and Swing Limit 1. The limit angle is symmetric. Therefore, a value of 20 will limit the rotation between -20 and 20 degrees.

twistSpan.title: Twist Limit
twistSpan.description: The Twist Limit limits the rotation around the twist axis. The limit angle is symmetric. Therefore, a value of 20 will limit the twist rotation between -20 and 20 degrees.

schema.name: footFriction
schema.title: Foot Friction
schema.description: Friction between your feet and other colliders. This helps to keep the character from sliding down slopes, and also helps the character move up slopes more quickly. Consider this the grip of your boots.

schema.name: bodyFriction
schema.title: Body Friction
schema.description: Friction between your body and other colliders. This friction applies when the character rubs up against colliders when falling or flying.

schema.name: airDrag
schema.title: Air Drag
schema.description: Slows the character down when it's in the air. Should remain very low to prevent gravity from feeling sluggish. Note that when grounded, air drag is combined with ground drag.

schema.name: groundDrag
schema.title: Ground Drag
schema.description: Slows the character down when it's grounded. When a character stops running, this drag helps to bring the character to a stand-still. Note that friction should be configured first so that the character doesn't slide off slopes. Then, ground drag can be added to further slow down movement.

schema.name: airAcceleration

schema.name: leapSpeedMultiplier
schema.title: Leap Speed Multiplier
schema.description: When jumping, this multiplier is applied to the character's velocity. This allows the character to push itself away when jumping, allowing it to leap greater distances.

schema.name: performancePollInterval
schema.title: Performance Poll Interval
schema.description: The interval in seconds at which the performance stats are polled for the current quality level.

schema.name: performanceInvalidationDelay
schema.title: Performance Invalidation Delay
schema.description: The duration in seconds after which the performance statistics of a quality level are considered invalid. This helps prevent frequent switching to a quality level with a consistently low average frame rate.

schema.name: frameRateThreshold
schema.title: Frame Rate Threshold
schema.description: The frame rate threshold is used to determine when the current quality level should be reevaluated. It is calculated as a percentage of the maximum frame rate. For example, if the threshold is set to 0.9 and the maximum frame rate is 60 FPS, the threshold will be 0.9 * 60 = 54 FPS. If the frame rate drops below this value, the quality level is switched down. Conversely, if the frame rate rises above this value, the quality level is switched up, provided that the higher quality level is considered suitable and won't perform poorly.
